Input Output Technique
In Java, we typically use an index pointer to avoid expensive string copying and erasing.

class Solution {
    public void solve(String ip, String op, int index) {
        // Base Case: We've made a decision for every character in the input
        if (index == ip.length()) {
            System.out.println("'" + op + "'");
            return;
        }

        // Option 1: EXCLUDE the current character
        // We just move to the next index without adding to op
        solve(ip, op, index + 1);

        // Option 2: INCLUDE the current character
        // we create a new string adding the character at the current index
        solve(ip, op + ip.charAt(index), index + 1);
    }
}




Efficiency Tip: StringBuilder

If the input string is very long, 
using op + char creates many String objects, 
which can be slow. 
For competitive programming, 
we often use a StringBuilder and backtracking:;

public void solve(String ip, StringBuilder op, int index) {
    if (index == ip.length()) {
        System.out.println(op.toString());
        return;
    }

    // Exclude
    solve(ip, op, index + 1);

    // Include
    op.append(ip.charAt(index)); // Action
    solve(ip, op, index + 1);    // Recurse
    op.deleteCharAt(op.length() - 1); // Backtrack (Undo Action)
}